		<table width="100%">
		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    Being a cleric, by Brayce of Xegony</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:Gokou67@aol.com">Vin</a> | 
		            8/9/1999 1:29:32 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">Being a cleric, by Brayce of Xegony<BR>
<BR>
First of all, if you want to be a cleric, you must choose a race.  It seems that Dwarven clerics are the best kind, but I have not expiremented with them as of yet.  I have only a human cleric, because I am quite fond of both Qeynos and Freeport.  But, as with all classes in Everquest, you will find that you can succeed with any race you choose to play.  This guide will be aimed mostly toward human clerics, but I tried to make it more general so anyone can use it to start off what is, in my opinion, the most fun class in Everquest.<BR>
<BR>
First off, choosing your deity.  This is not too important, but in the long run it may make a difference.  If you want to start in Freeport, choose Mithaniel Marr, if you want to start in Qeynos, choose Rodcet Nife.  That is basically all you need to know about choosing a deity.  Now, for choosing your city.  This is for you humans out there.  I really suggest Freeport, the reason being that you will have the best place to level up a little later on, and that is the dungeon Befallen.  It is only a short walk from Freeport, and it is filled with undead, and if you didn&#8217;t already know, killing undead is our specialty.  Ward undead, a level 5 spell, will do 35 damage to an undead creature, much more damage than you are doing with your weapon (guaranteed), and even more damage than any of the other classes direct damage spells on that level.  From here on out, I will mainly concentrate on telling you what to hunt in the Freeport area, as it is the area I know the best, but for all you High Elf  and Dwarf clerics out there, I will throw in a few tips (as best I can) for the Greater Faydark area.  As I am also getting to know the Qeynos area pretty well, I will throw in a few tips on that region as well. <BR>
<BR>
Levels 1-4<BR>
On level 1, 2, 3, and 4, you will basically want to fight rats, bats, decaying skeletons, and snakes, with the occasional orc pawn thrown in (which can be found in the Faydark, Freeport, and even in front of Kaladim, for you Dwarfs).  You will also want to fight Widow Hatchlings and Fire Beetles on these levels, as they give good loot and experience, but be warned, for you in the Faydark, widow hatchlings will poison you, so be careful.  Also, when you get to level 4, you will probably want to fight mainly Orc Pawns, as they give the best loot (cloth armor and rusty weapons), for your level.  Now for some combat tips.  Always use courage, although you may not notice it, it adds to your HP and AC, making you tougher to kill, you will be using it up until level 9, when you get Center.  Second, don&#8217;t be afraid to use Minor Healing.  I have seen many low-level clerics run from a battle before trying to heal.  If your HP gets low, use your healing spell, that&#8217;s why you&#8217;re a Cleric and not a Warrior.  If you die, don&#8217;t worry, you will get no penalty until level 5.  Second, as soon as you have saved up a few gold, go buy Strike from your local Cleric spell vendor.  This spell will usually do somewhere around 5 damage (it can do more, this is just a rough estimate).  Once you have this spell, always use it to start a battle.  No more chasing things around with your club, Hit them with Strike and ready your weapon as they charge at you.  Next, buy a better weapon.  I would suggest buying a rusty morning star if you can find one, I used it a lot on low levels, and I find that it is better than the rusty mace that many carry.  Next, you will want armor, this part may come a little after level 5, but I would suggest skipping cloth and saving up for patchwork or leather.  You may want to train 10 points in tailoring and make yourself some patchwork, as it is cheaper to make than leather is to buy (as long as you have a good tailoring skill, failing costs you money), and the AC is only one or two less than leather.  The problem with this is that you will have to find ruined pelts.  If you are human, go into the east commons and find a group to kill pumas (be at least level 5 for this), they will give ruined cat pelts, which make human sized armor.  If you are highelf or dwarf, it will be easier to find wolves around your area, as their pelts will be your size.  That&#8217;s it for my little section on tailoring, should you decide to use it.<BR>
<BR>
Levels 5-8<BR>
Clerics get much more fun on level 5, as does any class when you get your first NEW spells.  Don&#8217;t you feel powerful now?  Good, but don&#8217;t go trying to kill any griffins just yet.  If you are a Elf or Dwarf, I suggest going to Greater Faydark, and finding a group to hunt with right outside Crushbone.  If you are in freeport, You will probably want to group in the East Commons to kill Pumas, and maybe rattlesnakes, that is if you have the Cure Poison spell, it will come in handy, but save your mana, it will take only one casting to cure feeble poison, but 2 castings to cure weak poison (rattler's poison) and 3 to cure regular poison (asps, don&#8217;t fight asps just yet, they are too hard).  Still, I have found it useful, especially when soloing rattlesnakes and asps (not for level 5's).  You could try to group and go to befallen, but I have found that on this level, you will die too much for the hunting to be worth it, try grouping there on levels 8 or 9.  If you get bored of killing Pumas, go buy Ward Undead if you don&#8217;t already have it, and go to the ruins (behind the second inn if you follow the path on the left from Freeport).  You will find many skeletons there, stronger than their decaying cousins, but using ward undead will cut them down to size.  I love seeing &quot;You hit a Skeleton for 35 points of damage&quot;, when your wizard friends are hitting for 18.  But be careful, and don&#8217;t fight too close to the ruins, because if a lesser mummy or zombie appears, he will probably slaughter your whole group, unless you have a full party and you are fairly powerful (not all level 5's).  And if a Ghoul appears, run like mad, cause you most likely don&#8217;t have a magic weapon, and 99 percent of the time, he&#8217;s gonna kill your whole party before you can get to the guards at the inn.  If you haven&#8217;t already, buy cure disease and cure poison, sure it&#8217;s a few gold, but you will probably use them enough.  I have a made several platinum when people need a cure rabies, I quickly memorize the spell, and more often than not, they pay you a few gold as a reward, if you listen up for shouts needing a cure, you will more than likely make enough money to pay for the spell, along with plenty extra.  If you happen to be in Qeynos area, the best thing to do at around level 8 is to find a good hunting partner, and go kill giant snakes in BlackBurrow.  The exp is good and the loot is great for your level.  They drop snake fangs and venom sacs worth about 4gp each.  When I used to make hunting runs there with my friend we would each make about 5pp (with some looting luck of course) in an hour when the snake ledge in BB was not crowded.  <BR>
<BR>
Levels 9-13<BR>
Once you hit level 9, you will probably be able to solo some of those snakes, but I would advise waiting till level 10, when you can easily crush them all.  Now here are the spells you are going to want on level 9.  Definitely buy center.  When you cast this on someone who doesn&#8217;t know how powerful it is,  you will get a lot of wows.  On level 9, it raised my HP from 180 to 224, that will keep you alive a lot longer.  But don&#8217;t forget to keep holy armor memorized, its still nice to have that extra AC and at this point the mana cost is pretty low for you as long as you have a good wisdom.  The other spells you will want are root, which becomes very useful as soon as you learn where and when to cast it.  I would not suggest buying fear as it is not used too often, but this is your decision.  You will also want to buy summon food which will be cheap and since it is a level 1 spell for the magician class, I bought it at the magician guild, it may be the same price at the cleric guild, but I haven&#8217;t checked.  One spell that supposedly is good but I have only used a few times, Word of Pain, I bought this and to be honest I think it was a complete waste of money.  It does only 5 or 6 more damage than furor and costs a heck of a lot more mana, also it is point blank area effect so don&#8217;t plan on casting it on a running opponent, just root him and cast furor, costs about the same mana =).  At this point, you will need to save up around 7pp for each lvl 14 spell you want, plus this is a good time to think about buying some good armor.  I would advise buying banded.  The AC is good and it is fairly cheap, you can get bronze if you want but it is significantly heavier and more expensive.  Now, you will probably be wanting a better weapon, well I have one word for you, Bloodforge.  If you have any 2h blunt skill you will want to do this quest.  I will not explain it in detail here as you can read about it on www.everlore.com under the quests section, but you can easily complete it if you can get to Kaladim and get your faction up (took me and a friend about 3 real hours of killing goblins to get the hammers).  If you are thinking about a one handed weapon, save up a lot of money and buy a screaming mace and a shiny brass shield, which is an excellent combination and the weapon is great, but I would not suggest trying to save for that just yet.  A few clerics i've seen use the level 9 summoned hammer, Hammer of Wrath, which to me seems like a waste of money and not too good, except that it does hit magical.  I am currently on level 11 so I cannot tell you much more but I will continue this guide once I hit around 19 or so.  Thank you for reading and I hope you enjoy your life as a cleric.<BR>
<BR>
Brayce<BR>
Cleric of Xegony<BR>

